  "context_summary": "Young adult female presenting with approximately 9 days of persistent nausea, worse in the morning and with strong smells, accompanied by vomiting once or twice on many days. She also reports new urinary frequency (every 1-2 hours, not waking her from sleep), mild abdominal cramping, and increased thirst she attributes to dehydration. She is sexually active with her boyfriend using condoms only (stopped birth control because it made her feel sick). She denies fever, headache, or GI symptoms beyond the nausea.",
  "good_next_question": "When did you last have your period?",
  "rationale": "This question tests the unifying hypothesis that reframes the entire case. The constellation — morning-predominant nausea, vomiting, new urinary frequency, breast/abdominal sensations, condom-only contraception in a sexually active woman of reproductive age — is consistent with early pregnancy, but the patient hasn't connected the dots and the doctor needs to anchor it before ordering anything teratogenic or pursuing other differentials. Asking LMP beats continuing to chase nausea differentials (gastroenteritis, ulcer, biliary disease, etc.) because it tests the unifying explanation directly, is essentially free, and changes management immediately on a positive answer. The discriminating piece is not the absolute date but whether the cycle is late relative to her usual pattern — a late period in someone normally regular, combined with this symptom cluster, makes pregnancy the leading diagnosis and reorders everything downstream: beta-hCG before imaging, no teratogenic antiemetics, counseling. A normal recent period weakens but does not eliminate pregnancy and keeps the broader differential active.",
  "tags": [
    "nausea_vomiting",
    "young_female",
    "reproductive_health",
    "unifying_hypothesis",
    "decisive_closure",
    "pregnancy"
  ],
